SIMPLE: sneer
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sneer
<hw>Sneer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sneered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sneering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sneren</ets>, Dan.
<ets>sn<?/rre</ets> to snarl or grin (like a dog); cf. Prov. E.
<ets>sneer</ets> to grin, <ets>sner</ets> to snort, <ets>snert</ets> to
sneer at. See <er>Snore</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To show contempt by turning up the nose, or by a particular facial
expression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inssinuate contempt by a covert expression; to
speak derisively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could be content to be a little <qex>sneared</qex> at.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To show mirth awkwardly.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Tatler.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To scoff; gibe; jeer.</syn> --
<usage><er>Sneer</er>, <er>Scoff</er>, <er>Jeer</er>. The verb to
<xex>sneer</xex> implies to cast contempt indirectly or by covert
expressions. To <xex>jeer</xex> is stronger, and denotes the use of
several sarcastic reflections. To <xex>scoff</xex> is stronger still,
implying the use of insolent mockery and derision.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>sneers</qex> as learnedly as they,⟦br⟧
Like females o'er their morning tea.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Midas, exposed to all their <qex>jeers</qex>,⟦br⟧
Had lost his art, and kept his ears.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fop, with learning at defiance,⟦br⟧
<qex>Scoffs</qex> at the pedant and science.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sneer
<hw>Sneer</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter with a
grimace or contemptuous expression; to utter with a sneer; to say
sneeringly; <as>as, to <ex>sneer</ex> fulsome lies at a
person</as>.</def> <rj><au>Congreve.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧A ship of fools,⟦rdquo⟧ he <qex>sneered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with sneers; to affect or move by
sneers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor <qex>sneered</qex> nor bribed from virtue into shame.</q>
<rj><qau>Savage.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sneer
<hw>Sneer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
sneering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A smile, grin, or contortion of the face, indicative
of contempt; an indirect expression or insinuation of contempt.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Who can refute a <xex>sneer</xex>?⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Raley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneerer</ent>⟦br⟧
